```rust
fn handle_why(id: &str, show_summary: bool, limit: usize) {
    let path = default_events_path();
    let Ok(events) = read_tail_events(&path, limit) else {
        // ... cold start handling ...
        return;
    };
    if show_summary {
        println!("{}", build_state_summary(&events));
        println!();
    }
    match build_why_report(&events, id) {
        Ok(report) => println!("{report}"),
        Err(e) => {
            let mut msg = format!("{YELLOW}  {e}{RESET}");
            if limit > 0 && events.len() >= limit {
                msg.push_str(&format!(
                    "\n{DIM}(note: only the most recent {limit} events were scanned; the target may be further back — retry with --limit 0){RESET}"
                ));
            }
            eprintln!("{msg}");
        }
    }
    // ... limit note ...
}
```

Now, here's the thing: `build_why_report` already handles some "no failure" cases with helpful messages. For example, when `failure_count == 0` and `run_completed_count > 0`, it says "N successful sessions recorded. No failure data to diagnose." and suggests `yoyo state crashes`. 

But the task wants additional information: when there are incomplete runs (RunStarted without RunCompleted), surface those with run IDs and timestamps. The `build_why_report` doesn't do this — it gives generic counts but not specific run IDs.

My approach: In the `Err` branch of `handle_why`, when `id == "last-failure"`, scan for incomplete runs and report them with diagnostic next-steps.

